Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 475 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @Roma Tomato{1}(diced). Trim and thinly slice @Scallions{2}(thinly sliced). Quarter @Lime{1%whole}. Core, deseed, and dice @Green Bell Pepper{1}(diced).

In a small #bowl{}, combine tomato, scallions, a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tbsp}, and juice from one lime wedge (two wedges for 4 servings). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

In a separate small bowl, combine @sour cream{2%tbsp} with lime juice to taste. Add @water{1%tsp} at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add bell pepper, salt, and pepper; cook until just softened, ~{6%minutes}. Transfer to a third small bowl.

Add another drizzle of @cooking oil{}, @ground pork{10%oz}, half the @Tex-Mex Paste{1%whole}, @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tbsp}, salt, and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{6%minutes}.

> If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it out.

Return bell pepper to pan; stir to combine. Turn off heat.

Place a small amount of filling on one half of each @flour tortillas{6}. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create enchiladas.

Place seam sides down in an 8-by-8-inch #baking dish{} (9-by-13-inch dish for 4 servings) or an #ovenproof pan{}.

== Sauce ==

In a bowl or #liquid measuring cup{}, combine @water{1/2%cup}(for 4 servings, use 3/4 cup), @tomato paste{1.5%oz}, remaining Tex-Mex paste, and remaining Southwest Spice.

Pour over enchiladas to thoroughly coat. Sprinkle with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}.

Bake on top rack until sauce is bubbly and cheese has melted, ~{5%minutes}.

== Lime Crema & Pico de Gallo ==

Top enchiladas with lime crema and pico de gallo. Divide between #plates{} and serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> When it comes to Mexican-style food, burritos typically get all the glory. In our humble opinion, enchiladas are a total unsung dinner hero. Technically easier-to-assemble burritos smothered in a delicious sauce, these weeknight wonders offer so much more than "food on the table." This Tex-Mex version is filled with a combo of spiced pork and bell pepper, topped with a bold red sauce and Mexican cheese, then baked until bubbly and melty. With a finishing touch of fresh pico and lime crema, that's a whole 'lada deliciousness.